<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Safety Paper" class="currentChild" href="Safety_Paper">Safety Paper</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
Paper especially formulated with a protective background to show erasures, or other means to expose forgery or document alterations, such as paper used for checks, bonds, bank slips, coupons, tickets, warranties, and legal forms. They must possess high <a title="Durability" href="Durability">durability</a>, in particular paper used for checks, which must withstand payer and payee handling, as well as check-sorting equipment. (See also <a title="MICR Check Paper" href="MICR_Check_Paper">MICR Check Paper</a>.) The <a title="Basic Size" href="Basic_Size">basic size</a> of safety papers is 17 x 22, and comes in a <a title="Basis Weight" href="Basis_Weight">basis weight</a> of 24-pound. 
</p>
